So y'all know how old I am. Oops. That's how I can remember. Get your calculator. Yeah, Hawaii became a state in 1959. And so there were Hawaiian natives. They didn't separate out the natives and say, no, you're not American citizens. So the American natives and the Hawaiian natives are U.S. citizens. They already enjoy all of the everything that other American citizens enjoy. They vote and everything else. Now, the Native American Indians were a conquered people, pretty much. I mean, at that time, we had treaties with them. And that was a whole mess, too. But we had treaties with them, gave them separate land, actually forced them onto land that was not their native land and all that. There's a lot of injustice. But they were kind of treated like a conquered people and then separated out completely from the rest of the country and treated very differently for, you know, well over 100 years. So this is a very different situation. It is a different situation. Hawaiians came in as full citizens. In fact, they've had representation. Daniel Akaka is a Native Hawaiian senator. So representation. So it's certainly mainstreamed. And so the idea that our administration, who's always talking about inclusiveness, who's always talking about, you know, bringing us together, you know, it sounds good. They say one thing and they're doing something totally different. Doing the exact opposite. He is saying what we want to hear. We do believe that in America. Right. We have been the big melting pot. But instead, I think he wants us to be a big salad bowl. Yeah. I think a lot of people voted for him because they thought he was going to bring the country together. And it's not worked out that way, in my opinion. Right. Well, and either we have a constitution or we don't. And if somebody moves into Hawaii, say from South America or, you know, another country, aren't they going to go through the same process to become a naturalized citizen of the United States? And aren't they going to make a pledge to the constitution as well? And does this constitution not apply to them anymore? Right. Yeah. Exactly. Do they do this if they start treating citizens differently? Well, you know, isn't it just so strange? Because none of it makes sense. It doesn't make sense. They're making up the rules as they go along. This administration is doing some of the weirdest stuff. I mean, every administration does some weird stuff. But these guys are just kind of making up the rules as they go along, ignoring the constitution right and left, ignoring the Bill of Rights. I don't understand why people aren't more angry about it. I mean, there are a lot of angry people. You know, maybe they all need a radio show. Well, you know, I do think that people are becoming more and more concerned. Instead of defining us by what brings us together, it seems that this administration is trying to define us by what separates us. And, you know, we have this group of women that we all get together and talk and, you know. And recently, one of the things that comes up is people are concerned about the divisiveness. Yeah, I think whenever you start to separate people out by their ethnic groups, colors of their skin, you're not, you're certainly not bringing the country together. Definitely. So we just wanted to bring that forward to all of you. And if you have any comments, the conversation. The assumption on this is that the commander in chief is protecting the Constitution as well. That the purpose is the same. And also, okay, I'm sorry, does such a chip exist? Boy, gosh, you would think we'd have heard about that a long time ago. Are they developing? I think you had some timeline, Kim, for the development of this chip. So if this chip is being developed and it's so great at mental illness, why wouldn't we want those chips to be implanted in a whole bunch of other people as well? Why just military? So they're launching a five-year program. And per a Scientific American article that I saw, it says the Obama administration has committed $110 million next year and possibly billions over the next decade to what they call the BRAIN Initiative. And this stands for Brain Research Through Advancing Innovative Neurotechnologies. Talk about controlling us by our health care. So what, the military is the guinea pig? She began to spasm, went into convulsions, went into a coma, ended up dying from the whole thing. She had numbness, paralysis, motor weakness. After her final session, it said she became incoherent, slimped into a coma, and died. Yeah. And he was so enthusiastic. He was so enthusiastic to report he had induced the same type of seizure in a human that Farrier had achieved in animals.
